# Unity UI Toolkit DesignSystem

- New menus, panels, HUDs, overlays, navigation, and runtime UI screens must be built with UI Toolkit using `UIDocument`, UXML, and USS.
- Every new screen root must use the `ds-root` class and attach the project's `DesignSystem.uss` stylesheet.
- Do not reference this rules repository as a design system asset source; the design system assets must live inside the target Unity project.
- Use existing `ds-*` component classes for buttons, inputs, cards, modals, drawers, tabs, badges, navigation, icons, feedback, and common controls.
- Use DesignSystem tokens for color, spacing, radius, typography, borders, and motion; do not hard-code one-off visual values in feature USS.
- Feature USS is allowed only for feature-specific layout or a component that does not exist in the DesignSystem yet.
- If the DesignSystem is missing a required visual pattern, extend the project's DesignSystem first instead of recreating a local lookalike in a feature folder.
- Runtime UI code may bind view models, refresh state, toggle classes, apply visibility/animation state, and emit input intent; it must not make gameplay, economy, reward, or progression decisions.
- Keep `VisualElement`, `Q`, `Query`, and UI Toolkit callbacks inside `Presentation`; `Domain` and pure `Application` must not know UI Toolkit types.
- Use stable ids, localization keys, or view model fields for UI content; do not bind behavior to UXML hierarchy indexes, sibling order, display text, or icon names.

## Example

```xml
<!-- GOOD: screen root uses the project DesignSystem -->
<ui:VisualElement class="ds-root inventory-screen">
  <ui:Button name="buy-button" class="ds-btn ds-btn--primary" text="Buy" />
</ui:VisualElement>
```

```csharp
// GOOD: Presentation emits intent and toggles visual state.
var buyButton = root.Q<Button>("buy-button");
buyButton.clicked += () => _presenter.RequestBuySelectedItem();
buyButton.Enable(_presenter.CanBuySelectedItem);
```
